MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: apps/(lobby/lib/email-templates|nudge-worker/src/index)\.ts$
MATCH_CONTENT: style=
ADVISORY: |
  Inline-style double-quote trap in email HTML.

  Template literals render HTML where `style="..."` is delimited by
  double quotes. Double-quoted font names (`"Helvetica Neue"`,
  `"Arial Black"`, `"Segoe UI"`) interpolated into the style attribute
  terminate it early. Every property after the first inner `"` is
  silently dropped by the browser.

  Symptom: font stays as browser default, text-transform:uppercase
  disappears, font-size reverts, text-decoration:none fails, etc.
  The element still renders — just with a subset of intended styles.
  No warnings, no errors.

  Wrong — inner double quotes break the attribute:
    const DISPLAY = `Impact, "Helvetica Neue", "Arial Black", sans-serif`;
    `<p style="font-family:${DISPLAY};font-size:48px;font-weight:900;">`

  Right — single quotes inside the style value:
    const DISPLAY = `Impact, 'Helvetica Neue', 'Arial Black', sans-serif`;

  Any multi-word font name in a stack that gets interpolated into a
  `style="..."` attribute MUST be single-quoted at the source. Applies
  to both email-templates files (lobby + nudge-worker are copy-pasted).

  Debug hint: if preview text renders in wrong font / wrong size /
  wrong case, grep the file for `"[A-Z][a-z]+ [A-Z]` inside backtick
  strings — that's the pattern of a double-quoted font name.
